This data is mostly numerical with category of countries, 8 variables, and some missing pieces. It is the human development section of a collection of data found at https://www.kaggle.com/undp/human-development It is from the United Nations Development Program and centers around the Human Development Index (HDI); the geometric mean of normalized indices for the data variables of life expectancy, educatiion, and Gross National Income

Potential problems/questions include:

  • Does missing some data for certain countries allow them to have a potentially higher HDI ranking than they may deserve? (Does the HDI have flaws in it's validity?)
  • Does increasing education help the Gross National income increase?
  • Are all variables carrying the same weight in the HDI? (How is the HDI calculated exactly?)

Current chosen problem: What one change in what one country increases life expectancy most?

n = X_HDI.shape[0]

X = X_HDI[perm]
y = y_HDI[perm]
X_test_HDI = X[:test]      
y_test_HDI = y[:test]
X_train_HDI = X[test:]    
y_train_HDI = y[test:]

b, m = reg.intercept_, reg.coef_
b, m

plt.plot(X_test_HDI, y_test_HDI, 'b+')

yy = b + m*xx
plt.plot(xx, yy, 'r-');
print('The training R2: {}'.format(reg.score(X_train_HDI, y_train_HDI)))

n = X.shape[0]
test = int(0.20*n)            # We will use a test set made up of 20% of the data from our sample
perm = rn.permutation(n)   
X = X[perm]
y = y[perm]
R2 = pa.DataFrame( np.array([ [0]*5, [0]*5, [0]*5, [0]*5, [0]*5, [0]*5, [0]*5, [0]*5]).transpose(), 
                  columns = ['train_HDI', 'test_HDI', 'train_ExEd', 'test_ExEd', 'train_MeEd', 
                             'test_MeEd', 'train_GNI', 'test_GNI' ])
# Making a DataFrame to record the R2 values in

for k in range(5):
    X_test = X[k*test:(k+1)*test]       # Then create the test
    y_test = y[k*test:(k+1)*test]
    X_train = np.concatenate( (X[:k*test], X[(k+1)*test:]), axis=0)     # and train sets
    y_train = np.concatenate( (y[:k*test], y[(k+1)*test:]), axis=0)
    reg_HDI = LinearRegression().fit(X_train_HDI, y_train)
    reg_ExEd = LinearRegression().fit(X_train_ExEd, y_train)
    reg_MeEd = LinearRegression().fit(X_train_MeEd, y_train)
    reg_GNI = LinearRegression().fit(X_train_GNI, y_train)
    
    R2.loc[k, 'train_HDI'] = reg_HDI.score(X_HDI, y_HDI)
    R2.loc[k, 'test_HDI'] = reg_HDI.score(X_HDI, y_HDI)
    R2.loc[k, 'train_ExEd'] = reg_ExEd.score(X_ExEd, y_ExEd)
    R2.loc[k, 'test_ExEd'] = reg_ExEd.score(X_ExEd, y_ExEd)
    R2.loc[k, 'train_MeEd'] = reg_MeEd.score(X_MeEd, y_MeEd)
    R2.loc[k, 'test_MeEd'] = reg_MeEd.score(X_MeEd, y_MeEd)
    R2.loc[k, 'train_GNI'] = reg_GNI.score(X_GNI, y_GNI)
    R2.loc[k, 'test_GNI'] = reg_GNI.score(X_GNI, y_GNI)

R2mean = [0]*8
R2std = [0]*8
for c in range(4):
    R2mean[c] = np.mean(R2.iloc[0:5, c])
    R2std[c] = np.std(R2.iloc[0:5, c])
    
R2 = R2.append( pa.Series(R2mean, index=R2.columns), ignore_index=True )
R2 = R2.append( pa.Series(R2std, index=R2.columns), ignore_index=True)
R2.index = [0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 'Mean', 'Standard Deviation']

I edited the example a lot on this one because I don't want to compare every piece of data like the example did. This had drawbacks in that my resultant output doesn't quite look right to me. My ultimate goal is to determine which singular change in which singular country will increase life expectancy the most. In applying that to this homework assignment, I am taking all relevant variables in the dataset and using cross validation to see which regression model has the strongest correlation to the life expectancy variable. This means taking out the HDI rank, Country, Life Expectancy, and GNI-HDI variables, and using regression models for the HDI, Expected years of education, Mean years of education, and GNI variables. It took a while to get the output to look somewhat close to correct, but there are still issues I need to find out how to resolve. For example, the test and training sets appear to have the same values, which is an issue. There are also low and negative numbers, which I believe to result from my inability to successfully get my data shaped into a 0-1 range. It may be more than that though, as the MeEd (Mean Education) and GNI have the same mean but are very different in correlation coefficient and line matching on their graphs. With this shaky foundation for analysis established, I can conclude based on current appearances that (assuming that a number further from 0 is better) the best model I have for predicting life expectancy is my HDI regression. This also matches with the original linear regression correlation coefficient.

perm = rn.permutation(n)

y = y[perm]
X_test = X[:test]      
y_test = y[:test]
X_train = X[test:]     
y_train = y[test:]
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsRegressor
def plot_reg_model(reg, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test):
    h = 0.01 
    x_min, x_max = -0.1, 1.1
    y_min, y_max = -0.1, 1.1
    xx, yy = np.meshgrid(np.arange(x_min, x_max, h),
        np.arange(y_min, y_max, h))
    Z = reg.predict(np.c_[xx.ravel(), yy.ravel()])
    Z = Z.reshape(xx.shape)
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    plt.contour(xx, yy, Z)
    plt.scatter(X_train[:, 0], X_train[:, 1], c=y_train, marker='o')
    plt.scatter(X_test[:, 0], X_test[:, 1], c=y_test, marker='+');
    print('Training R2: {}'.format(reg.score(X_train, y_train)))
    print('Testing R2: {}'.format(reg.score(X_test, y_test)))
reg = KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=2)
reg.fit(X_train, y_train)
plot_reg_model(reg, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test)
plt.savefig('11.11.png')
reg = KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=10)
reg.fit(X_train, y_train)
plot_reg_model(reg, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test)
plt.savefig('11.12.png')
reg = KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=20)
reg.fit(X_train, y_train)
plot_reg_model(reg, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test)

Initial Thoughts¶

I used the regression adaptation of K nearest neighbors to plot four different Ks for the data variable with the most correlation with life expectancy (expected years of education). The first was a situation where K=1, so the fantastic training correlation there is not to be believed (data points are comparing themselves to themselves).

Sections are fairly well defined, though they become less so as K grows. The correlation also shrinks with the larger K values. I wanted to check to see how it looked with other variables. This is what followed:

Hitting a Wall¶

Making these nearist neighbors regressors was easy enough, but I hit a snag on the part where I use cross validation or bootstrapping to look at how helpful they are. I could not seem to get out of the world of error messages, and my code got so messy and complicated that I was struggling to keep track of it. A lot of this was due to null values in my data and the limits of my correlations themselves (they were neither as strong nor as worthwhile as I'd hoped, and there just wasn't enough data).

So, instead, I am trying again with a different kind of K nearest neighbors on a different dataset (the Iris measurement one) and bootstrapping:

    Error_std[c] = np.std(Error.iloc[:num, c])
